&quot;This Selected Leave Plan is already accepted.&quot;
&quot;This Selected Leave Plan is already rejected.&quot;

In my opinion, only the selectedLeavePlan == null check should be in the widget, the rest of logic should be done in a Service method, which returns a MessageList, and the widget just raises any messages

if(selectedLeavePlan != null)
    MessageList&lt;Messages&gt; messages = service.acceptAdjudication(selectedLeavePlan);
    Messages.raiseMessages(messages);
} else {
AbsenceWidgetUtils.raiseSelectObjectMessage()
}

Recently I was working on Employment business entity which extends from OCOccupationExtensionBase which is front office entity.
So since the parent class is using the @UseDeprecatedNamingStrategy so even the child class has to use @UseDeprecatedNamingStrategy.
Now if you are using the Rel in the entity then aspectj will expect it to be in some fashion otherwise it will not work.

So if the Rel is 1..1 then it expect below getter methods:
@Deprecated
      public Rel&lt;BusinessEntity&gt; getManager() {
            final Rel&lt;BusinessEntity&gt; retVal = RelRef.create(this, &quot;manager&quot;);
            return retVal;
      }

      public BusinessEntity getManagerItem() {
            return manager;
      }

Here Item word is expected by aspectj.
Similarly if the Rel is List then aspectj expects the word List at the end of the getter method.

